
[1]echo

   ECH'O, n. [L. echo; Gr.sound, to sound.]

   1. A sound reflected or reverberated from a solid body; sound returned;
   repercussion of sound; as an echo from a distant hill.

   The sound must seem an echo to the sense.

   2. In fabulous history, a nymph, the daughter of the Air and Tellus,
   who pined into a sound, for love of Narcissus.

   3. In architecture, a vault or arch for redoubling sounds.

                  ECH'O, v.i. To resound; to reflect sound.

   The hall echoed with acclamations.

   1. To be sounded back; as echoing noise.

   ECH'O, v.t. To reverberate or send back sound; to return what has been
                                  uttered.

   Those peals are echoed by the Trojan throng.
